1. Core Architecture of Transitions
For a CSS transition to work, two things must be present:

The Target Property: The CSS value you want to animate (e.g., background-color, transform, width).

The Trigger Event: A structural pseudo-class selector that initiates the shift (most commonly :hover, :active, or :focus).

2. The Four Transition Sub-Properties
You can configure a smooth state shift using four individual sub-properties:

transition-property: Specifies the exact name of the CSS property you want to animate. You can specify a unique attribute (like background-color) or use the keyword all to animate every single changing property simultaneously.

transition-duration: Dictates how long the smooth interpolation takes to complete. It accepts values in seconds (s) or milliseconds (ms). (e.g., 0.3s or 300ms).

transition-timing-function: Manages the mathematical acceleration curve of the transition. Common preset curves include:

linear: Constant speed from start to finish.

ease (Default): Starts slow, speeds up in the middle, and washes out slowly at the end.

ease-in: Starts slow and accelerates aggressively until it hits the final state.

ease-out: Starts fast and decelerates into a gentle stop at the end.

ease-in-out: Symmetrical slow start and slow end.

cubic-bezier(n,n,n,n): Allows you to define completely custom velocity maps using coordinate vectors.

transition-delay: Sets a distinct waiting threshold (in seconds or milliseconds) before the transition animation actually begins playing.

3. The Clean Industry Shorthand (transition)
To keep your production stylesheets maintainable and scannable, you should combine all four sub-properties into a single shortcut declaration:

CSS
/* Shorthand Order: property | duration | timing-function | delay */
.button {
  transition: all 0.3s ease-in-out 100ms;
}
Animating Multiple Properties Separately
If you want different properties to change at completely different speeds on the same element, chain your shorthand properties using a comma (,):

CSS
.card {
  /* Scale up instantly, but fade the color background change slowly */
  transition: transform 0.1s linear, 
              background-color 0.5s ease-out;
}
4. Comprehensive Student Code Lab: Interactive Hover Card
Copy this standalone HTML/CSS script directly into VS Code to observe how transitions cleanly interpolate layout dimensions:

HTML
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>CSS Transition Lab</title>
    <style>
        * {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            box-sizing: border-box;
        }

        body {
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            min-height: 100vh;
            background-color: #f1f3f5;
            font-family: sans-serif;
        }

        /* 1. Style the baseline normal state */
        .interactive-card {
            width: 280px;
            padding: 2rem;
            background-color: #ffffff;
            color: #333333;
            border-radius: 12px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 6px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
            cursor: pointer;

            /* Set up the global transition shortcut */
            transition: all 0.4s cubic-bezier(0.25, 0.8, 0.25, 1);
        }

        /* 2. Style the triggered end state */
        .interactive-card:hover {
            background-color: #007bff; /* Morphs background to blue */
            color: #ffffff;            /* Flips text string to white */
            transform: translateY(-8px) scale(1.03); /* Lifts element up */
            box-shadow: 0 15px 30px rgba(0, 123, 255, 0.3); /* Expands shadow frame */
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="interactive-card">
        <h3>Naman Gupta</h3>
        <p style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 0.9rem; opacity: 0.8;">
            Hover over this bounding container box to watch multiple properties transition smoothly at the same time.
        </p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>